Currently, "Done" means "Finished without error" including skipped. Not arguing for or against, that's just the status quo. I don't use this trigger rule so I think it's best if folks that do weigh in!
+1 on my end. Ran it and I don't see zombies anymore (https://github.com/airbnb/airflow/issues/1157)

Yeah I'm running into this issue as well. It seems like just importing the CeleryExecutor in the code requires the configuration to be there even if it is not used. 
https://github.com/airbnb/airflow/blob/master/airflow/executors/celery_executor.py#L29

As a follow up, when enabling the logs, I also need to add `worker_log_server_port`. The celery call will fail and it will default to the s3 logs. If I don't set that variable though, an unhandled exception is generated when accessing the logs.

@lamdrew The intention was yes - "ALL_DONE" means the task has been evaluated. This include success, failure, skipped, etc... Skipped is a form of evaluation because it is skipped based on a condition. It sounds like you need another trigger rule. Please provide an example of your DAG and what you are trying to achieve. There is probably a work-around.

To be honest I'm not sure if we have ever "officially" supported relative directories. It's a messy proposition given that Airflow uses many subprocesses in its execution and while they will _probably_ share a working directory, I'm not sure that's guaranteed. In any case `git bisect` shows the commit that broke it was 8f06cf8 by @mistercrunch and I actually modified that code further in #1271.
